Both additions are correct and cleanly placed. Here's a summary of exactly what was done:

---

### Changes made — `common/chat.cpp` only

**1. New handler function** (inserted at line 1519, before the `workaround` namespace):

```cpp
static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(
        const common_chat_template &          tmpl,
        const autoparser::generation_params & inputs) {
    common_chat_params data;

    data.prompt            = common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl(tmpl, inputs);
    data.format            = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_PEG_NATIVE;
    data.supports_thinking = false;
    data.preserved_tokens  = { "[INST]", "[/INST]", "</s>" };

    auto parser = build_chat_peg_parser([&](common_chat_peg_builder & p) {
        auto end = p.end();
        return p.literal(inputs.generation_prompt) + p.content(p.rest()) + end;
    });

    data.parser = parser.save();
    return data;
}
```

**2. Detection entry** (inserted in `common_chat_try_specialized_template`, after GigaChatV3, before `return std::nullopt`):

```cpp
if (src.find("[INST]") != std::string::npos &&
    src.find("[/INST]") != std::string::npos &&
    src.find("[SYSTEM_PROMPT]") == std::string::npos) {
    LOG_DBG("Using specialized template: mistral-instruct-v3\n");
    return common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(tmpl, params);
}
```

**Design decisions:**

- **Detection** matches the two hallmark tokens of the v0.3 instruct template (`[INST]`/`[/INST]`) and uses the *absence* of `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` to stay clear of the existing Ministral/Magistral Large 3 handler, exactly as specified.
- **`preserved_tokens`** keeps `[INST]`, `[/INST]`, and `</s>` from being split by the tokenizer, since they are structural to the wire format.
- **No reasoning / no tool machinery** — Mistral Instruct v0.3 is a plain conversational format; `supports_thinking = false` and no grammar/trigger wiring are appropriate here.
- **No existing handler or header file was modified.**

